<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,438,967]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,474,499]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Notes.</emphasis>
This species described from Fort Collins, Larimer Co., 
<collectingRegion box="[905,1009,474,499]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Colorado</collectingRegion>
and its two valid subspecies 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell 1921" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1921" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="alpha" subSpecies="dialpha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. alpha dialpha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[245,419,510,535]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref85927" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1921) Western bees obtained by the American Museum expeditions. American Museum Novitates, 24, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1921">Cockerell 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Cockerell 1921" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1921" box="[477,870,510,535]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="alpha" subSpecies="paralpha">
<emphasis box="[477,687,510,535]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. alpha paralpha</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[696,870,510,535]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref85927" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1921) Western bees obtained by the American Museum expeditions. American Museum Novitates, 24, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1921">Cockerell 1921</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(both from Walden, 
<collectingRegion box="[1111,1217,510,535]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Colorado</collectingRegion>
) are currently only known from that state (
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[409,598,546,571]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="69 - 85" refId="ref85766" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1905 a) Bees of the genus Nomada found in Colorado, with a table to separate all the species of the Rocky Mountains. Colorado Agricultural Experiment Station. Bulletin, 94, 69 - 85." type="journal article" year="1905" yearSuffix="a">
Cockerell 1905 
<bibRefCitation author="a" box="[585,668,546,571]" firstAuthor="a" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 15" refId="ref85927" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1921) Western bees obtained by the American Museum expeditions. American Museum Novitates, 24, 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="1921" yearSuffix="a">a, 1921</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Swenk" box="[680,823,546,571]" firstAuthor="Swenk" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 113" refId="ref103969" refString="Swenk, M. H. (1912) Studies of North American bees. I. Family Nomadidae. University Studies of the University of Nebraska, 12, 1 - 113." type="journal article" year="1912">Swenk 1912</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hurd" box="[833,958,546,571]" firstAuthor="Hurd" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1741 - 2209" refId="ref90811" refString="Hurd, P. D. (1979) Superfamily Apoidea. In: Krombein, K. V., Hurd Jr., P. D., Smith, D. R. &amp; Burks, B. D. (Eds.), Catalog of Hymenoptera in America North of Mexico. Smithsonian Institution Press, Washington, D. C., pp. 1741 - 2209." type="book chapter" year="1979">Hurd 1979</bibRefCitation>
). The close proximity of the 
<typeStatus box="[1280,1328,547,571]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">type</typeStatus>
localities (within approximately 
<quantity box="[413,502,582,607]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" unit="km" value="100.0">100 km</quantity>
) for all the subspecies, including two from near Walden, Jackson Co., 
<collectingRegion box="[1325,1432,582,607]" country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Colorado</collectingRegion>
, does not fit the standard concept of subspecies as being geographically separated populations. There seems to be a close affinity with 
<taxonomicName authority="Cresson" authorityName="Cresson" authorityYear="1863" box="[367,615,654,679]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliterata">
<emphasis box="[367,512,654,679]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. obliterata</emphasis>
Cresson
</taxonomicName>
, although that species is unusual for having only two submarginal cells and differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1905" box="[342,440,690,715]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpha">
<emphasis box="[342,440,690,715]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. alpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in several respects, such as clypeal sculpture, hind tibial setae, and color. As is the case for many 
<taxonomicName box="[262,357,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[262,357,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Nomada</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species as currently recognized, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1905" box="[734,832,726,751]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpha">
<emphasis box="[734,832,726,751]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. alpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its putative subspecies requires additional study. Note that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1905" box="[271,373,762,787]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpha">
<emphasis box="[271,373,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. alpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[600,808,762,787]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="69 - 85" refId="ref85766" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1905 a) Bees of the genus Nomada found in Colorado, with a table to separate all the species of the Rocky Mountains. Colorado Agricultural Experiment Station. Bulletin, 94, 69 - 85." type="journal article" year="1905" yearSuffix="a">Cockerell (1905a)</bibRefCitation>
with the epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1905" box="[1016,1080,762,787]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpha">
<emphasis box="[1016,1080,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">alpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spelled in letters whereas the infrasubspecific name of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1903" box="[437,630,798,823]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphaerogaster">
<emphasis box="[437,630,798,823]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. sphaerogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[790,995,798,823]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="189 - 191" refId="ref85813" refString="Cockerell, T. D. A. (1905 b) Some bees of the genus Nomada from Wisconsin. The Canadian Entomologist, 37, 189 - 191. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 37189 - 5" type="journal article" year="1905" yearSuffix="b">Cockerell (1905b)</bibRefCitation>
in that same year from 
<collectingRegion box="[1267,1384,798,823]" country="United States of America" name="Wisconsin" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Wisconsin</collectingRegion>
was designated originally with a symbol Î±. We regard the former as valid and the latter as an unavailable name (see 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1903" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphaerogaster">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">N. sphaerogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
